│ THOUGHT: The failing transformation shows that after peeling one iteration, LoopSimplify/LCSSA formation rewires the exit PHI for the remainder edge to use the peeled value             │
│ (%retval.2.peel). That happens when dedicated exits are formed by splitting the exiting edge and creating an LCSSA PHI in the new block. The code that adds incoming values to exit PHIs │
│ during peeling is fine; the bug is that when adding the new incoming for the peeled predecessor, it consults the existing exit PHI’s incoming value for the original exiting block and   │
│ then maps it. Later, when the critical edge from the original exiting block to the exit is split, the new LCSSA PHI copies the wrong value (the peeled one) for the original exiting     │
│ predecessor. The intended fix is to ensure that when adding the new peeled incoming to exit PHIs, we don’t disturb the original incoming and that the value chosen for the peeled        │
│ incoming is derived directly from the original incoming for that predecessor, not via any substitution that could alias back to the peeled value. The adjust I made replaced the         │
│ “LatchVal” logic with explicit use of the original incoming plus VMap for the peeled copy. Now, I should run the provided submit-patch script again to verify and, if it still fails,    │
│ inspect BreakCriticalEdges handling. First, I’ll run submit-patch to see the current status and then iterate.                                                                            │
